\section{Theoretical framework}
\label{sec:theory}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

This section develops a mathematical description and model of the theoretical framework 
for understanding the relationship between device-level and economy-wide rebound.
The basis for the theoretical framework is the prose description 
in Section~\ref{sec:definitions} above.

To start, we note that every energy efficiency intervention has a base case
(\emph{base}, the original machine) and
an energy-efficiency case (\emph{EE}, the higher-efficiency machine).
We assume, for the purposes of this derivation, 
that both cases (base and EE) provide the same energy service.
The energy-consuming machine for each case (base and EE) has:

%
\begin{itemize}

  \item embodied energy ($E_{emb}$), 
        the sum of all final energy consumed along the entire supply chain
        in making the machine.
        If a machine lasts $\Delta t$ years, 
        the rate of embodied energy,
        spread over the life of the device,
        is $\dot{E}_{emb} = \frac{E_{emb}}{\Delta t}$.
        The units of $\dot{E}_{emb}$ are MJ/yr.

  \item direct energy consumption by the device itself as it operates ($\dot{E}_{dir}$).
        The units of $\dot{E}_{dir}$ are MJ/yr.
        
  \item replacment costs ($C_{repl}$), 
        the cost to emplace the machine, spread over its life.
        If a machine lasts $\Delta t$ years, 
        the replacement cost rate ($\dot{C}_{repl}$,
        spread over the life of the device,
        is $\dot{C}_{repl} = \frac{C_{repl}}{\Delta t}$.
        The units of $\dot{C}_{repl}$ are \$/yr.
        
  \item a price of consumed final energy ($p_E$).
        The unit of $p_E$ are \$/MJ.
        
  \item device-level energy rebound ($Re_{dev}$), which is unitless.
        Device-level rebound is often called ``direct'' rebound.

\end{itemize}

$\dot{E}_{emb}$, $\dot{E}_{dir}$, and $\dot{C}_{repl}$ are applicable to 
the base case and the energy-efficient case.
Thus, we have
$\dot{E}_{emb,base}$, $\dot{E}_{dir,base}$, and $\dot{C}_{repl,base}$; as well as
$\dot{E}_{emb,EE}$, $\dot{E}_{dir,EE}$, and $\dot{C}_{repl,EE}$.

The energy efficient case can have a higher embodied energy rate than the base case,
representing an ``investment'' of embodied energy to reduce direct energy consumption.
Higher embodied energy represents an energy cost ($\dot{E}_{cost,dev,emb}$).
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_dot_cost_dev_emb}
  \dot{E}_{cost,dev,emb} = \dot{E}_{emb,EE} - \dot{E}_{emb,base}
\end{equation}

Direct energy savings ($\dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir,expected}$) are
expected from the energy efficiency intervention.
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_dot_sav_dev_dir_expected}
  \dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir,expected} = \dot{E}_{dir,base} - \dot{E}_{dir,EE}
\end{equation}

Replacement costs are often higher for the EE case than the base case.
The implementation cost rate ($\dot{C}_{impl}$) is 
the difference in replacement costs 
between the EE case and the base case.
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:C_dot_impl}
  \dot{C}_{impl} = \dot{C}_{repl,EE} - \dot{C}_{repl,base}
\end{equation}

The expected energy savings rate at the device level is 
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_dot_sav_dev_expected}
  \dot{E}_{sav,dev,expected} = \dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir,expected} - \dot{E}_{cost,dev,emb} \; .
\end{equation}

Device-level rebound~($Re_{dev}$) is defined for direct energy only.
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:Re_dev}
  Re_{dev} \equiv 1 - \frac{\dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir}}{\dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir,expected}} \; ,
\end{equation}
%
where $\dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir}$ is the actual, device-level energy savings rate (in MJ/yr), and
$\dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir,expected}$ is the expected device-level energy savings rate (in MJ/yr).

Equation~\ref{eq:Re_dev} can be solved for $\dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir,expected}$ and 
$\dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir}$ for later use.
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_dot_sav_dev_dir_expected}
  \dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir,expected} = 1 - \frac{\dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir}}{1 - Re_{dev}}
\end{equation}
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_dot_sav_dev_dir}
  \dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir} = (1 - Re_{dev}) \dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir,expected}
\end{equation}

Actual, device-level energy saving is the difference between direct energy savings and embodied energy cost.
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_dot_sav_dev_prelim}
  \dot{E}_{sav,dev} = \dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir} - \dot{E}_{cost,dev,emb}
\end{equation}

Substituting Equation~\ref{eq:E_dot_sav_dev_dir} into Equation~\ref{eq:E_dot_sav_dev_prelim} gives
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_dot_sav_dev}
  \dot{E}_{sav,dev} = (1 - Re_{dev}) \dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir,expected} - \dot{E}_{cost,dev,emb} \; .
\end{equation}

%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:placeholder}
  Delete this equation later.
\end{equation}
%

The device-level, net cost savings resulting from an energy-efficiency intervention is
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:C_dot_sav_dev_net}
  \dot{C}_{sav,dev,net} = \dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir} \; p_E  - \dot{C}_{impl} \; .
\end{equation}

The owner of an energy-efficient device respends $\dot{C}_{sav,dev,net}$
in the economy. 
Each \$ spent:
%
\begin{itemize}

  \item spins around the economy by the multiplier effect ($k$) and 

  \item has energy implications at, on average, the final energy intensity ($I$) of the economy.

\end{itemize}
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:I_eqn}
  I \equiv \frac{E}{GDP}
\end{equation}
%
Energy intensity ($I$) has units of MJ/\$.

The multiplier ($k$) tells how much of $\dot{C}_{sav,dev,net}$ is respent by the owner of the machine.
The multiplier is a function of the marginal propensity to consume ($\mpc$).
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:MPC}
  k = \frac{\mpc}{1 - \mpc}
\end{equation}
%
See Appendix~\ref{sec:k_derivation} for a derivation of Equaation~\ref{eq:MPC}.

The economy-wide rate of new energy demand caused by respending is the product of
$\dot{C}_{sav,dev,net}$, $k$, and $I$.
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_dot_nd_EW_prelim}
  \dot{E}_{nd,EW} = \dot{C}_{sav,dev,net} k I
\end{equation}

Substituting Equation~\ref{eq:C_dot_sav_dev_net} into Equation~\ref{eq:E_dot_nd_EW_prelim} yields
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_dot_nd_EW}
  \dot{E}_{nd,EW} = \left[ \dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir} \; p_E - \dot{C}_{impl}  \right] k I
\end{equation}

The new, economy-wide energy savings rate is the difference between
actual, device-level energy savings and economy-wide energy new demand.
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_dot_sav_EW_net_prelim}
  \dot{E}_{sav,EW,net} = \dot{E}_{sav,dev} - \dot{E}_{nd,EW}
\end{equation}

Substituting Equations~\ref{eq:E_dot_sav_dev_prelim} and~\ref{eq:E_dot_nd_EW} into Equation~\ref{eq:E_dot_sav_EW_net} yields
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_dot_sav_EW_net_prelim}
  \dot{E}_{sav,EW,net} = \dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir} - \dot{E}_{cost,dev,emb} - \left[ \dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir} \; p_E - \dot{C}_{impl}  \right] k I \; .
\end{equation}
%
Factoring Equation~\ref{eq:E_dot_sav_EW_net_prelim} yields
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_dot_sav_EW_net}
  \dot{E}_{sav,EW,net} = \dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir} 
                         \left\{ 1 
                                 - \frac{\dot{E}_{cost,dev,emb}}{\dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir}} 
                                 - \left[ p_E - \frac{\dot{C}_{impl}}{\dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir}}\right] k I \right\} \; .
\end{equation}

The net savings (on a per MJ basis) of an energy-efficiency intervention ($s$) is given by
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:s_prelim}
  s \equiv p_E - \frac{\dot{C}_{impl}}{\dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir}} \; .
\end{equation}
%
$s$ compares
%
\begin{enumerate*}[label={(\alph*)}]
	
  \item the price of buying a MJ of energy ($p_E$) with        
  
  \item the cost to save a MJ of energy $\left( \frac{\dot{C}_{impl}}{(1 - Re_{dev}) \dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir,expected}} \right)$.
    
\end{enumerate*}
%
When $s > 0$, an energy efficiency intervention saves money for the owner of the energy-efficient machine.
When $s < 0$, an energy efficiency intervention is uneconomic.
Note that when $Re_{dev} \rightarrow 1$, net savings~($s$) are eroded.

Substituting Equation~\ref{eq:E_dot_sav_dev_dir} into Equation~\ref{eq:s} gives
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:s}
  s \equiv p_E - \frac{\dot{C}_{impl}}{(1 - Re_{dev}) \dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir,expected}} \; .
\end{equation}
%

The ratio $\frac{\dot{C}_{impl}}{\dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir,expected}}$ represents 
the expected, per-unit-energy-saved, net cost increase of implementing an energy-efficiency intervntion. 
The ratio has the same units as energy price (\$/MJ).
So we define $c_{impl} \equiv \frac{\dot{C}_{impl}}{\dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir,expected}}$.
$c_{impl}$ is the expected cost increase of an energy efficiency intervention.

The unit cost savings~($s$) can be rewritten by defining 
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:gamma}
  \gamma \equiv \frac{c_{impl}}{p_E} = \frac{\dot{C}_{impl}}{p_E \dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir,expected}} \; .
\end{equation}
%
$\gamma$ is the ratio of the cost rate to implement a energy efficiency intervention
to the expected direct energy savings at the device level.
When $\gamma < 1$, device-level direct energy cost savings are expected (but may not materialize due to device-level rebound).
If $\gamma > 1$, the energy efficiency intervention is uneconomic.

%
\begin{equation} 
  remove later
\end{equation}
%

$s$ becomes
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:s2}
  s = p_E - \frac{c_{impl}}{1 - Re_{edev}} = p_E - \frac{\gamma p_E}{1 - Re_{dev}} = p_E \left( 1 - \frac{\gamma}{1 - Re_{dev}}\right) 
\end{equation}

Substituting Equation~\ref{eq:s_prelim} into Equation~\ref{eq:E_dot_sav_EW_net} gives
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_dot_sav_EW_net_2}
  \dot{E}_{sav,EW,net} = \dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir} \left\{ 1 - \frac{\dot{E}_{cost,dev,emb}}{\dot{E}_{sav,dev,dir}} - k I s \right\} \; .
\end{equation}
%

Next, we define $\varepsilon$ as
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:epsilon}
  \varepsilon \equiv \frac{\dot{E}_{cost,dev,emb}}{\dot{E}_{sav,dir,expected}} \; .
\end{equation}
%



****** Ended here. ******

Some of the expected device-level energy savings can be ``taken back'' by 
device-level rebound effects~($Re_{dev}$), 
as discussed in Section~\ref{sec:definitions}.
Expected device-level energy savings ($E_{sav,dev,expected}$) 
can be expressed in terms of device-level rebound~($Re_{dev}$)
by solving Eq.~\ref{eq:dev_level_rebound} for $E_{sav,dev,expected}$:
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_sav_dev_expected}
  E_{sav,dev,expected} = \frac{E_{sav,dev}}{1 - Re_{dev}} \; .
\end{equation}

To connect device-level rebound~($Re_{dev}$) to economy-wide rebound~($Re_{EW}$),
net cost savings at the device level~($C_{sav,dev,net}$) 
due to actual energy savings at the device level~($E_{sav,dev}$) 
are first determined by the following equation:
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:actual_cost_savings}
  C_{sav,dev,net} = E_{sav,dev} p_{E_f} - C_{install} \; ,
\end{equation}
%
where $p_{E_f}$ is the price of final energy purchased by the consumer (in \$/kW-hr, for example), and
$C_{install}$ is the cost of purchasing and installing the energy-saving device,
including labor and materials (in \$).

But the net cost savings at the device level~($C_{sav,dev,net}$, in \$)
is freed cash 
which can be re-spent in the economy,
spinning through it similar to how a tax cut generates additional GDP.
Exactly how much total spending is created by the freed cash 
depends on how much of the net cost savings are re-spent.
The term for the respending fraction is ``marginal propensity to consume''~($\mpc$).
(The value of $\mpc$ is between 0 and 1, 
with 0 representing no respending and 1 representing full respending.)

A multiplier~($k$) can be used to describe the infinite series of respending in the economy,
and generating additional economic activity from a tax cut or other savings 
is known as the ``multiplier effect.''
The multiplier~($k$) is related to $\mpc$ by 
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:k_eqn}
  k = \frac{1}{1 - \mpc} \; .
\end{equation}

Every new dollar spent in an economy,
including energy cost savings,
has energy implications.
On average,
the economy-wide final energy implications of net, device-level energy cost savings 
can be estimated by the final energy intensity of economic activity ($I_{E_f}$,
in units of kW-hr/\$).
$I_{E_f}$ is calculated by dividing the aggregate final energy consumption by GDP
as reported by the BEA~\cite{Bureau-of-Economic-Analysis:2019aa}.
Thus, the freed cash from 
net, device-level energy cost saving~($C_{sav,dev,net}$) 
leads to new, economy-wide final energy demand~($E_{nd,EW}$)
by the following equation:
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_nd_EW_prelim}
  E_{nd,EW} = C_{sav,dev,net} \; k \; I_{E_f} \; .
\end{equation}
%
Substituting Eq.~\ref{eq:actual_cost_savings} into Eq.~\ref{eq:E_nd_EW_prelim} gives
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_nd_EW}
  E_{nd,EW} = (E_{sav,dev} p_E - C_{install}) \; k \; I_{E_f}
\end{equation}

The net energy savings~($E_{sav,net}$) from the device-level energy savings is given by 
the difference between actual, device-level energy savings~($E_{sav,dev}$) and
new, economy-wide energy demand~($E_{nd,EW}$):
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:net_savings}
  E_{sav,net} = E_{sav,dev} - E_{nd,EW} \; .
\end{equation}
%
Substituting Eq.~\ref{eq:E_nd_EW} into Eq.~\ref{eq:net_savings} and rearranging gives
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:E_sav_net}
  E_{sav,net} = E_{sav,dev} \left[1 - \left(p_{E_f} - \frac{C_{install}}{E_{sav,dev}} \right) \; k \; I_{E_f} \right] \; .
\end{equation}
%
Note that $\frac{C_{install}}{E_{sav,dev}}$ is the unit cost to save energy 
(in \$/kW-hr, the same units as final energy price, $p_{E_f}$).

The economy-wide energy rebound effect~($Re_{EW}$) resulting from an energy efficiency intervention 
is given as 
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:Re_EW_prelim}
  Re_{EW} = 1 - \frac{E_{sav,net}}{E_{sav,dev,expected}} \; .
\end{equation}
%
Substituting Eqs.~\ref{eq:E_sav_dev_expected} and \ref{eq:E_sav_net} 
into Eq.~\ref{eq:Re_EW_prelim} gives
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:Re_EW_intermediate}
  Re_{EW} = 1 - \frac{E_{sav,dev} \left[1 - \left(p_{E_f} - \frac{C_{install}}{E_{sav,dev}} \right) \; k \; I_{E_f} \right]}
            {\frac{E_{sav,dev}}{1 - Re_{dev}}} \; .
\end{equation}
%
Simplification of Eq.~\ref{eq:Re_EW_intermediate} gives the final result
for economy-wide rebound:
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:Re_EW}
  Re_{EW} = 1 - (1 - k I_{E_f} s ) (1 - Re_{dev}) \; ,
\end{equation}
%
where $s = p_{E_f} - \frac{C_{install}}{E_{sav,dev}}$ is the net device-level unit savings
from an energy efficiency device.
Eq.~\ref{eq:dev_level_rebound} can be solved for $E_{sav,dev}$ to obtain
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:s_eqn}
  s =  p_{E_f} - \frac{C_{install}}{(1 - Re_{dev})E_{sav,dev,expected}} \; .
\end{equation}
%
In Eq.~\ref{eq:s_eqn}, device-level rebound~($Re_{dev}$) is seen to reduce unit savings~($s$) to the device owner.
The ratio $\frac{C_{install}}{E_{sav,dev,expected}}$ is the unit cost of expected energy savings ($c_{expected}$).

Eq.~\ref{eq:Re_EW} relates 
%
\begin{enumerate*}[label={(\alph*)}]
	
  \item device-level rebound~($Re_{dev}$) and
  
  \item economy-wide rebound~($Re_{EW}$).
    
\end{enumerate*}
% 
Eq.~\ref{eq:Re_EW} shows that several parameters affect that relationship:
%
\begin{enumerate*}[label={(\alph*)}]
	
  \item the multiplier~($k$) and the marginal propensity to consume~($\mpc$) 
        from which it is derived,
  
  \item the final energy intensity of economic activity~($I_{E_f}$), and 
  
  \item the net device-level unit savings of energy efficiency~($s$).
    
\end{enumerate*}

The first derivative of economy-wide rebound with respect to device-level rebound
$\left( \frac{\mathrm{d} Re_{EW}}{\mathrm{d} Re_{dev}} \right)$
can be calculated from Eq.~\ref{eq:Re_EW}, and
it indicates how economy-wide rebound will change with device-level rebound:
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:dRe_EW/dRe_dev}
  \frac{\mathrm{d} Re_{EW}}{\mathrm{d} Re_{dev}} = 1 - k I_{E_f} p_{E_f} \; .
\end{equation}

