\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

The equations in Section~\ref{sec:theory} and 
the case study in Section~\ref{sec:case_studies}
enable the following observations.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Economy-wide energy backfire is observed}
\label{sec:backfire_observed}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Installation of LED bulbs is likely to cause economy-wide energy backfire 
when economy-wide rebound is considered, 
because Eq.~\ref{eq:Re_EW_val} shows $Re_{EW} > 1$.
**** Discuss how this result agrees (or doesn't) with other economy-wide backfire estimates
from the literature. ****


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Conditions for economy-wide backfire}
\label{sec:conditinos_for_backfire}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Economy-wide backfire occurs when $Re_{EW} > 1$, or, with reference to Eq.~\ref{eq:Re_EW},
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:backfire_inequality_1}
  1 - (1 - k I_{E_f} s) (1 - Re_{dev}) > 1 \; .
\end{equation}
%
Simplification gives
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:backfire_inequality_2}
  (1 - k I_{E_f} s) (1 - Re_{dev}) < 0 \; .
\end{equation}

It is expected that $Re_{dev} < 1$ and
$(1 - Re_{dev}) > 0$. 
If it were not so, 
energy efficiency interventions would be uneconomic for the efficiency device owner.
Thus, the inequality of Eq.~\ref{eq:backfire_inequality_2} simplifies to
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:backfire_inequality_3}
  1 - k I_{E_f} s < 0 \; .
\end{equation}
%
Solving for $s$ gives
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:backfire_inequality_4}
  s > \frac{1}{k I_{E_f}} \; .
\end{equation}
%
Substituting for $s$ from Eq.~\ref{eq:s_eqn} gives
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:backfire_inequality}
  p_{E_f} - \frac{C_{install}}{(1 - Re_{dev}) E_{sav,dev,expected}} > \frac{1}{k I_{E_f}} \; .
\end{equation}

Inspection of Eqs.~\ref{eq:backfire_inequality_4} and~\ref{eq:backfire_inequality} reveals that
economy-wide backfire is more likely to occur when
%
\begin{itemize}
	
	\item $s$ is large (it is economically advantageous for the energy efficiency device owner 
	      to install energy-efficient devices), which occurs when
	%
  \begin{itemize}

    \item $p_{E_f}$ is large 
          (energy is expensive),

    \item $Re_{dev}$ is small (rebound at the device-level is negligible), and
    
    \item $\frac{C_{install}}{E_{sav,dev,expected}}$ is small 
          (implementing energy efficiency is inexpensive relative to the expected energy savings);

  \end{itemize}
%
  \item $k$ is large, because $\mpc \rightarrow 1$ 
        (the multiplier effect is large, because nearly all freed cash is respent); and
  
  \item $I_{E_f}$ is large 
        (the economy is very energy intensive).
        
\end{itemize}


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{How to avoid backfire}
\label{sec:avoiding_backfire}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

When the purpose of energy efficiency is to \emph{reduce} energy consumption,
economy-wide backfire is undesirable.
Given the above results, 
this section uses the case study to explore
the sensitivity of economy-wide rebound to the various parameters in Eq.~\ref{eq:Re_EW}
and ways to avoid backfire.
In particular, the effects of 
the price of final energy~($p_{E_f}$), 
device-level rebound~($Re_{dev}$), 
the expected unit cost of an energy efficiency intervention~$\left(\frac{C_{install}}{E_{sav,dev,expected}}\right)$,
the marginal propensity to consume~($\mpc$), and 
final energy intensity~($R_{E_p}$)
are each considered in turn.


%------------------------------
